06202nam a22011175i 9780813544632DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20082008nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135446327 a10.36019/97808135446322doi  a(DE-B1597)529758  a(OCoLC)236079599  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHV4999.W65bN45 2008eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a362.2908222200aNeither Villain nor Victim :bEmpowerment and Agency among Women Substance Abusers /ced. by Tammy Anderson. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (244 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Issues in Crime and Society0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFemale drug addicts are often stereotyped either as promiscuous, lazy, and selfish, or as weak, scared, and trapped into addiction. These depictions typify the "pathology and powerlessness" narrative that has historically characterized popular and academic conversations about female substance abusers. Neither Villain Nor Victim attempts to correct these polarizing perspectives by presenting a critical feminist analysis of the drug world. By shifting the discussion to one centered on women's agency and empowerment, this book reveals the complex experiences and social relationships of women addicts. Essays explore a range of topics, including the many ways that women negotiate the illicit drug world, how former drug addicts manage the more intimate aspects of their lives as they try to achieve abstinence, how women tend to use intervention resources more positively than their male counterparts, and how society can improve its response to female substance abusers by moving away from social controls (such as the criminalization of prostitution) and rehabilitative programs that have been shown to fail women in the long term. Advancing important new perspectives about the position of women in the drug world, this book is essential reading in courses on women and crime, feminist theory, and criminal justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aDrug abusexPrevention. 0aDrug abusexTreatment. 0aFemale offendersxDrug use. 0aFemale offendersxRehabilitation. 0aWomen drug addicts. 0aWomen prisonersxDrug use. 0aWomen prisonersxRehabilitation. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Tammy L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Tammy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAnderson, Tammy.1 aBaskin, Deborah R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaskin, Deborah.1 aBerger, Michele Tracy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Michele Tracy.1 aBlankenship, Kim M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlankenship, Kim.1 aCoontz, Phyllis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoontz, Phyllis.1 aEttore, Elizabeth.1 aEttorre, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, Alison R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, Alison.1 aGreibel, Cate.1 aGriebel, Cate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartwell, Stephanie W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartwell, Stephanie.1 aKatsulis, Yasmina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKatsulis, Yasmina.1 aKelley, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelley, Margaret.1 aMalloch, Margaret S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalloch, Margaret.1 aMullins, Christ